<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate my freelance hourly rate?", answer: "Start with your target annual income, add business expenses and taxes, then divide by your annual billable hours. Billable hours equal your weekly billable hours times working weeks (52 minus vacation weeks). For example, if you need $100,000 total and can bill 1,200 hours per year, your minimum rate is about $83 per hour." },
  { question: "What percentage of time should be billable?", answer: "Most freelancers can only bill 60-70% of their working hours. The rest goes to marketing, administration, invoicing, and professional development. If you work 40 hours per week, plan for 25-30 billable hours. New freelancers may start even lower at 50% billable time." },
  { question: "Should I charge hourly or project-based rates?", answer: "Project-based rates are often better for experienced freelancers because they reward efficiency and remove the income ceiling of hourly billing. However, hourly rates are simpler for ongoing or unpredictable work. Many freelancers use hourly rates to scope projects, then present a fixed project price to clients." },
  { question: "How much should I add for taxes and expenses?", answer: "Freelancers typically need to add 25-35% for self-employment taxes on top of income tax. Business expenses like software, equipment, insurance, and workspace typically add another 10-20% to your costs. Always calculate your rate based on total costs, not just desired take-home pay." },
  { question: "How often should I raise my freelance rates?", answer: "Review your rates annually at minimum. Consider raising rates when you gain new skills or certifications, when demand for your services exceeds your capacity, after completing high-profile projects, or when your cost of living increases. Most successful freelancers increase rates by 5-15% annually." }
]) %>

